Sarajevo wasn’t just a siege — it was a window into what happens when suffering becomes entertainment for people insulated from consequence. Allegations of “sniper safaris” where wealthy foreigners paid to shoot civilians for sport aren’t only about the 90s; they expose a cold elite logic that turns human life into a commodity. That same distance shows up today when war is prolonged in lofty language, while quiet preparations begin to funnel the young and the poor into the meat grinder through conscription. When leaders gamble with escalation and ordinary people pay in bodies, the line between policy and atrocity gets dangerously thin.
